	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Thu, Oct 24th 3:08 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=145263><span id=Scholar>lunaticfringesk</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>311 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.43]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>I guess I am a little confused...<br><br>You comments seems to suggest that paladins cant solo at all.&nbsp;&nbsp;I can assure you, however, that they can, very well even, all the way to 60 (PoP is so new, cant make any conslusions yet).  You may want to re-think that statement.<br><br>Further, while I am the first to admit that I am not an expert on rangers, I feel very confident that they do NOT have the best snare.  I think there best snare is a 55% movement snare, with a 100ish HP DoT.  Compare that to an SK, however, and the difference is huge.  Dooming is a 60% snare, 300HP DoT, which is to say nothing about cascading.  Rangers get a root spell, however, but the duration and damage surely isnt anything that is dominating.  It is also &quot;broken&quot; often, reducing its effectiveness.<br><br>Isnt dooming and cascading darkness snares?  Im very much confused by your statement that darkness isnt as good as snare.  Also, darkness snares seldom &quot;break&quot; as roots do.  <br><br>Additionally, the long casting time is offset by the DoT that they do.  Also, darkness is typically what you are pulling with, so casting time isnt too big a deal there.<br><br>And, as stated in my earlier message, no way does a ranger solo a mob like Yeldema in WW (but Ive seeen numerous SKs though).  He tries to snare him, even if it lands, he'll get summoned and beat to a pulp (most likely).<br><br>Luna</p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
